coteminas fabric production making the consolidated company the worlds largest homefurnishings manufacturer in the end the merger that formed springs global us put the company in a position to survive the dramatic decline of the us textile industry industry analysts say what did springs get out of the deal the lowcost production capabilities of its brazilian partner coteminas bowles had become the fifth generation of the springs family to run the company in  she served  years as chief executive of an independent springs industries at the time of her appointment industry watchers speculated that she was brought in to make the tough decisions cutting jobs and closing plants as the nation in  saw an end to the international textile quota system which had limited imports from lowwage countries when the nations borders were thrown open to inexpensive hometextile imports springs pillowtex corp jp stevens and other us textile companies couldnt compete in the first of bowless strategies to stay afloat in a sea of inexpensive homefashion textile imports the family formed a partnership with an investment fund to take the company private springs formed its first alliance with coteminas in  as more production moved off shore springs global began rapidly shuttering us plants starting in  with the closing of the lyman plant in lyman sc and the wamsutta plant in anderson sc eliminating  jobs it concluded with the end of all manufacturing in its home state in  as production was halted at the grace plant in lancaster and the close plant in fort lawn the closing of these plants reflects the global nature of the textile industry which has made us textile manufacturing uncompetitive bowles said in a prepared statement at the time the final closings were announced though inevitable for the company this move is a sad and difficult one for my family and the people and communities involved we would like to express our deepest appreciation to all the associates for their years of commitment and productive efforts for this company in between was the loss of  jobs at the frances and elliott plants in fort lawn and the katherine plant in chester in  springs employed  in south carolina now  springs global workers remain in south carolina mostly at distribution centers in fort lawn and lancaster and at the former springs industries headquarters in fort mill although she remains on the springs global board bowles has started a parttime post as a senior advisor to the nc department of commerce her job is to monitor nc businesses competitiveness in various industry sectors bowless husband former charlotte investment banker erskine bowles is the president of the campus unc system despite bowles and the close familys virtual departure from springs global both will be forever linked to the fort mill area where family land holdings count in the thousands of acres on plus acres between interstate  and the catawba river the family built a successful neotraditional neighborhood called the village of baxter it was one a series of villages planned for family land in the area charlotte news  charlotte business journal menu select a city national albany albuquerque atlanta austin baltimore birmingham boston buffalo charlotte chicago cincinnati columbus dallas dayton denver greensborowinstonsalem honolulu houston jacksonville kansas city los angeles louisville memphis miamifort lauderdale milwaukee minneapolisst paul nashville new york orlando philadelphia phoenix pittsburgh portland raleighdurham sacramento san antonio san francisco seattle silicon valley st louis tampa bay washington dc wichita limited time offer subscribe now search × close sign in sign in your account your account welcome your account sign in existing users create your free account dont have an account your account subscriptions newsletters custom notifications my custom site manage site users sign out sign in sign in your account search home industries  topics all industries  topics banking  financi